Kate Hoff Shutta

About

I am a graduate student pursuing a Ph.D. in Biostatistics at UMass - Amherst.

Research

My interest is in the development and assessment of network methods for high-dimensional datasets, with the goal of contributing to advances in public health.

I currently work as a graduate student research assistant on the NIH grant Development and application of a metabolomics profile of chronic distress to cardiometabolic risk (NIH R01 AG051600 01A1, Co-PIs: Susan E. Hankinson, Sc.D., Laura D. Kubzansky, Ph.D.; Co-investigator: Raji Balasubramanian, Sc.D.). This study evaluates metabolomics profiles associated with chronic distress among women enrolled in the Nurses Health Study and the Womens Health Initiative.

I am also a graduate student research assistant on the NIH grant "Network Models for Metabolomics" (NIH R01 LM013444-01, Co-PIs: Raji Balasubramanian, Sc.D., Denise Scholtens, Ph.D.). As part of this work, I am developing methods for network estimation and differential network analysis with applications to metabolomics datasets.
